⸻

Bridge Principle

Qualitative phenomena become mathematically tractable when encoded into structure:
	•	vectors (feature encoding)
	•	embeddings (semantic geometry)
	•	graphs (relational structure)
	•	transformations (dynamic systems)

Examples:
	•	emotion → (valence, arousal, direction)
	•	language → embedding space
	•	perception → feature maps
	•	social systems → networks

⸻

Compression Warning

All qualitative → quantitative translation is lossy

	•	nuance is reduced
	•	context is partially flattened
	•	lived experience is not fully captured

This framework acknowledges and preserves that limitation.

⸻

The CPU Operator (Proposed)

Formal Definition

A ≈ B ⟨C, P, U⟩

Where:
	•	A, B = entities, states, claims, or models
	•	C = context (assumptions, environment, domain)
	•	P = perspective (observer, agent, interpretive frame)
	•	U = uncertainty (confidence, probability, resolution)

⸻

Interpretation

“A is approximately or operationally equivalent to B
under context C, from perspective P, with uncertainty U.”

⸻

Why This Matters

Current math:

A = B

Real-world truth:
	•	depends on context
	•	depends on observer
	•	carries uncertainty

The CPU operator makes these first-class, not hidden.

⸻

Canonical Examples

Scientific Modeling

light_wave ≈ light_particle ⟨measurement setup, observer model, 0.81⟩

Policy Comparison

policy_A ≈ policy_B ⟨economic recession, worker perspective, 0.62⟩

Semantic Similarity

dog ≈ wolf ⟨biological taxonomy, human perspective, 0.88⟩


